[h3 id=Comments 
	" Comments
	$LF
]h3
[h4 id=FastestAdvanceSpeed 
	" Fastest Advance Speed
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"Jet advances the fastest when no clouds or walkable ground comes into scrolling. Seas don't affect it. The final void space slows it down but there is nothing to do.
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=WeakerChargedShot 
	" Weaker Charged Shot
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"Release B button for at least 1 frame after a charged shot is out, and the shot will vanish after hitting anything.
	$LF
	"Just used in this run for fun.
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=JumpingOnTheSea 
	" Jumping on the Sea
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"The game allows the robot to walk on the "beginning part" of the sea so a new player can take time to react when the character dashes off the land onto the sea.
	$LF
	"It is glitchy that the walkable part of the sea is repeated every 256 pixels, so the character can land on it saving some precious fuel over the sea.
	$LF
	"The safe zone is relatively small considering the high speed, and a jump will span more than 256 pixels. To maximize fuel-saving, consecutive jumps are used in this run.
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=EnemiesSpawn 
	" Enemies Spawn
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"Every kind of lesser enemies and bosses spawns according to some very complicated rules.
	$LF
	"Basically new kinds of enemy waves and bosses only appear when there are no lesser enemies (inlcuding their projectiles) are on screen and some timer and scrolling contions are met.
	$LF
	"And the exact configuration of the lesser enemies can be manipulated according to the PRNG, which is affected by the gamepad input.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"As the goal of this game is to destroy the bosses, they are manipulated to appear as fast as possible.
	$LF
	"Enemy waves are be abused to align the timings of the conditions for the bosses.
	$LF
	"Some noticeable examples:
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		" 
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Right before the final boss appears, an enemy projectile is kept on screen to adjust the timings.
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[h4 id=ScreenWrap 
	" Screen Wrap
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"As in many 8-bit games, the player's shots can hit targets on the opposite edges of the screen.
	$LF
	"The first boss is destroyed on the top edge of the screen with a charged shot downwards diagonally.
	$LF
	"This is faster than to fly through its barrage, which blocks charged shots, to have a close-range shot.
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=DeathWarp 
	" Death Warp
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"By suciding when the first boss is destroyed, the gameplay will continue on the "moon" stage and the cutscene that the character flies up to outer space will be skipped.
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=PerishTogetherOrNot 
	" Perish Together, or Not
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"Our heroic robot didn't perish together with the final boss. It survived as the count of rest lives indicated.
	$LF
	"This "heroic-but-pointless sucide" was originally meant for the satire as mentioned above.
	$LF
]div
